Finding optimal number of clusters

Clustering algorithms: http://home.deib.polimi.it/matteucc/Clustering/tutorial_html/index.html

More information on Kmeans clustering algorithms: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IuRb3y8qKX4

Supervised vs Unsupervised classification algorithms: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CCJfSizX6RE

Source

Data for this example comes from a reanalysis of microarray data from the following paper: AtCIPK8, a CBL-interacting protein kinase, regulates the low-affinity phase of the primary nitrate response. (Hu et al.,2009)

** This example uses a subset of the data (significant DE genes), otherwise calculations take too long.

The script reads a CSV table of normalized expression values, with genes as rows and conditions as columns. The preferred format of the columns is as follows:

Genotype_Condition_Replicate#

The script will group together samples from same the group (Genotype & Condition) and take the mean of all replicates

Initialize variables

#WD <- setwd("~/Desktop/PlantGenomeMeetings/DPF_Dec01/")
ExpressionTable <- read.csv("Data/Normalized_MAexpression_Hu_2007_ATH1_chl1_Significant.csv",header = T,row.names = 1)
DecideK <- NA #Change this to number of clusters desired (between 1 and number of genes in table)
#DecideK <- 5

Using regular expressions to group samples and calculate mean expression

#head(ExpressionTable)
Groups <- gsub("R[0-9].*$","",colnames(ExpressionTable))
Groups <- unique(Groups)
# Calculate mean 
x <- list()
for (each in Groups){
  tmpCols <- grep(each,colnames(ExpressionTable))
  x[[each]] <- apply(ExpressionTable[,tmpCols],1,mean)
}
meanNormExprs <- do.call("cbind",x)

write.csv("MeansNormalized_MAexpression_Hu_2007_ATH1_chl1_Significant.csv",x = meanNormExprs,row.names = T)

exprsData <- meanNormExprs

Next part of the code was adapted from the post Optimal number of clusters in www.r-bloggers.com.

Elbow method plot

mydata <- meanNormExprs 
wss <- (nrow(mydata)-1)*sum(apply(mydata,2,
                                  function(x){var(x,use = "complete")}))
for (i in 2:15) wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(mydata,
                                     centers=i)$withinss)
plot(1:15, wss, type="b", xlab="Number of Clusters",
     ylab="Within groups sum of squares")

Decide number of clusters

If no initial K is set, it will default to the number of groups in the data.

if (is.na(DecideK)){
    DecideK <- ncol(mydata)
    paste("Default number of clusters: ",DecideK,sep = "")
  } else {
    paste("User defined number of clusters: ",DecideK,sep = "")#User input, based on
  }
## [1] "Default number of clusters: 4"

Hierarchical Clustering of genes

d <- dist(mydata, method = "euclidean") # distance matrix
fit <- hclust(d, method="ward") 
## The "ward" method has been renamed to "ward.D"; note new "ward.D2"
plot(fit,cex=0.7) # display dendogram
# Cut the tree  
groups <- cutree(fit, k=DecideK) # cut tree into clusters
# draw dendogram with red borders around the 5 clusters 
rect.hclust(fit, k=DecideK, border="red")

Clustering

Calculate the correlation between genes, do MDS scaling (Principal Components) and test different numbers of K.

# --
### 
meanNormExprs <- t(meanNormExprs)
correlation = cor(meanNormExprs, method = 'pearson')    
dissimilarity = 1 - (correlation)
distance = as.dist(dissimilarity)

# get first 2 pricipal componenets
xy = cmdscale(distance)
n = nrow(meanNormExprs)

# percentage of variance explained by clusters
p.exp = rep(0,n)

# minimum correlation among all components in each cluster  
min.cor = matrix(1,n,n)  

for (i in 2:n-1) {
  fit = kmeans(xy, centers=i, iter.max=100, nstart=100)
  p.exp[i] = 1- fit$tot.withinss / fit$totss
  
  for (j in 1:i) {
    index = fit$cluster == j
    min.cor[i,j] = min(correlation[index,index])
  }
}
p.exp
## [1] -2.220446e-16  9.548700e-01  9.680802e-01  0.000000e+00
min(which(p.exp > 0.9))
## [1] 2
# minimum number of clusters such that correlation among all components in each cluster is at least 40%
# will not always work
min(which(apply(min.cor[-1,],1,min,na.rm=T) > 0.4)) + 1
## [1] 4
## Plot
library(cluster)
min(which(p.exp > 0.9))
## [1] 2
par(mfrow=c(2,2))


fit = kmeans(xy, DecideK, iter.max=100, nstart=100)
clusplot(xy, fit$cluster, color=TRUE, shade=TRUE, labels=F, lines=0, plotchar=F, 
         main = paste(round(DecideK),'Clusters',sep=" "))

fit = kmeans(xy, round(DecideK*1.25), iter.max=100, nstart=100)
clusplot(xy, fit$cluster, color=TRUE, shade=TRUE, labels=F, lines=0, plotchar=F, 
         main = paste(round(DecideK*1.25),'Clusters',sep=" "))

fit = kmeans(xy, round(DecideK*1.5), iter.max=100, nstart=100)
clusplot(xy, fit$cluster, color=TRUE, shade=TRUE,  lines=0, plotchar=F, 
         main = paste(round(DecideK*1.5),'Clusters',sep=" "))

fit = kmeans(xy, round(DecideK*2), iter.max=100, nstart=100)
clusplot(xy, fit$cluster, color=TRUE, shade=TRUE,  lines=0, plotchar=F, 
         main = paste(round(DecideK*2),'Clusters',sep=" "))

Plot of suggested number of clusters

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
fit = kmeans(xy, min(which(p.exp > 0.9)), iter.max=100, nstart=100)
clusplot(xy, fit$cluster, color=TRUE, shade=TRUE, labels=F, lines=0,  plotchar=F, main = paste("Optimum Number of Clusters",sep=" "))

2 clusters explain > 90% of the variance between genes.
